const oryx_path_planning::Point &  origin,
const OccupancyGridCloud &  cloud 
) throw (OccupancyGridAccessException)

Creates a new OccupancyGrid which uses a supplied PointCloud as its base.

Author:
Adam Panzica
Parameters:
xDimThe size of the occupancy grid in some integer unit in the x-axis
yDimThe size of the occupancy grid in some integer unit the y-axis
zDimThe size of the occupancy grid in some integer unit the y-axis
resolutionA conversion factor to go from the integer unit representation to an engineering unit representation
originThe origin of the occupancy grid, in integer unit coordinates
cloudThe PointCloud to use as the base for the occupancy grid
Exceptions:
OccupancyGridAccessExceptionIf there is a point in the PointCloud that doesn't fit in the specified occupancy grid size

This constructor takes a PointCloud, which may or may not have its points in any particular order, and copies it into the PointCloud which backs this occupancy grid. In the process it organizes the points in such a fashion as to make them accessible quickly by <x,y,z> coordinates without the need for iteration and comparison. Since there is no built in provision to bounds-check the XYZ data in the Points in the given PointCloud, this constructor will throw an exception if a Point in the PointCloud falls outside the grid specified by the xDim, yDim and zDim parameters.

Definition at line 243 of file OccupancyGrid.cpp.

boost::shared_ptr< std::string > oryx_path_planning::OccupancyGrid::toString ( int  sliceAxis,
int  slice 
) const

Generates a string representation of a slice of the Occupancy Grid.

Author:
Adam Panzic
Parameters:
sliceAxisThe axis to create the slice along. O=x-axis, 1 = y-axis, 2=z-axis
sliceThe distance along the slice axis to make the slice
Returns:
A shared pointer to a std::string containing an ASCII-art representation of the occupancy grid slice specified

Prints out the specified slice of the occupancy grid in ASCII art with each character representing a point on the grid. For example, with xDim=Ydim=2.5 and resolution = .25, and all points set to UNKNOWN, the returned string will look like this:

UUUUUUUUUU
UUUUUUUUUU
UUUUUUUUUU
UUUUUUUUUU
UUUUUUUUUU
UUUUUUUUUU
UUUUUUUUUU
UUUUUUUUUU
UUUUUUUUUU
UUUUUUUUUU

The RGBA to ASCII mapping is as follows: | RGBA | ASCII | | :----: | :-----: | | UNKNOWN | 'U' | | FREE_LOW | ' ' | | FREE_HIGH| '_' | | OBSTACLE | 'X' | | GOAL | 'G' | | INFLATED | 'x' | | Non-Std | '*' |
